{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566241"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:37:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:37:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18727"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18727"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.4,0.03,0.13,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77144"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11459"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62650"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1710"},{"type":"tags","id":"2053"},{"type":"tags","id":"5607"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26532"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77144"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is undergoing elective total hip replacement under general anaesthesia. Two hours into the procedure, her core temperature is 35.4\u00b0C. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications are amlodipine and paracetamol. On examination, her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 12/min controlled, SpO2 98% on mechanical ventilation, and temperature 35.4\u00b0C. The ambient theatre temperature is 20\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Electric heating pad","Forced-air warming device","Circulating-water mattress","Increase ambient theatre temperature","Warmed intravenous fluids"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has developed mild hypothermia during surgery, defined as a core temperature below 36.0\u00b0C. Perioperative hypothermia is common and associated with increased risk of surgical site infection, cardiac complications, coagulopathy, and prolonged recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForced-air warming\u003C/strong\u003E devices are the most effective method of active warming during surgery. These devices blow warm air through a blanket placed over or under the patient, providing convective heat transfer. They are easy to use, safe, and have been shown to effectively prevent and treat perioperative hypothermia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing ambient theatre temperature\u003C/strong\u003E is less effective than forced-air warming and may cause discomfort for the surgical team. While maintaining an appropriate theatre temperature (typically 20-23\u00b0C) is important, it should not be the primary intervention for treating established hypothermia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarmed intravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E are important in preventing further heat loss but are less effective than forced-air warming for actively raising core temperature. They should be used in conjunction with other warming methods rather than as the sole intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECirculating-water mattresses\u003C/strong\u003E are less effective than forced-air warming devices because they only warm the parts of the body in direct contact with the mattress. Additionally, pressure points may reduce local blood flow and limit heat transfer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectric heating pads\u003C/strong\u003E have limited effectiveness and carry a risk of thermal injury, particularly in anaesthetised patients who cannot respond to temperature sensation. They are not recommended for intraoperative use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active warming should be initiated when core temperature falls below 36.0\u00b0C during surgery.","Forced-air warming devices are the most effective method of active warming during surgery.","Even mild perioperative hypothermia increases the risk of surgical site infection, cardiac complications, and coagulopathy."],"references":["Riley, C. et al, Inadvertent perioperative hypothermia. BJA Education, Volume 18, Issue 8, 227 - 233. Available from: https://www.bjaed.org/article/S2058-5349(18)30061-1/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62650"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18727"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62650"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T10:10:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T10:11:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11459"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77144"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda